{
  "doc_id": "13220",
  "text": "The observed warming in the Peninsula shows a clear seasonal dependence [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] [CITATION_7] [CITATION_8] , though warming occurs in all seasons. The Peninsula temperature trend in austral fall (MAM) and winter (JJA) is larger than that in spring (SON) and summer (DJF). This is true for both CW-and MBCCbased estimates. Note that the MAM temperature trend based on the MBCC data set is almost twice that based on the CW data set, an inconsistency likely attributable to differences in their interpolation methods, discussed above. The ensemble-mean temperature trend also exhibits similar seasonal variations, albeit somewhat smaller than observations.",
